<emphasis id="5FF7EAB8FF8DFF9DFF79F9748B5D6AD4" box="[151,319,1685,1709]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="455">Andrena spolata</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="09124B5BFF8DFF9DFEAAF9748B826AD4" author="Warncke, K." box="[324,480,1685,1709]" pageId="4" pageNumber="455" pagination="1 - 110" refId="ref24222" refString="Warncke, K. (1968) Die Untergattungen der westpalaarktischen Bienengattung Andrena F. Memorias e Estudos do Museu Zoologico da Universidade de Coimbra, 307, 1 - 110." type="journal article" year="1968">Warncke, 1968</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
; 12. male genitalia.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="6D3C36AAFF8DFF9CFF29F93A8E7D6D1C" blockId="4.[151,1437,1755,2034]" lastBlockId="5.[151,1437,151,430]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="456" pageId="4" pageNumber="455">
For direct species diagnosis, in the female sex the combination of an almost entirely shiny scutum and scutellum together with short semi-squamous hairs and without red-marked terga (excluding 
<taxonomicName id="AA834D29FF8DFF9DFB80F91E8E806B60" authorityName="Schmiedeknecht" authorityYear="1900" box="[1134,1250,1791,1817]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Andrena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="455" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arsinoe">
<emphasis id="5FF7EAB8FF8DFF9DFB80F91E8E806B60" box="[1134,1250,1791,1817]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="455">A. arsinoe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="AA834D29FF8DFF9DFAF7F91E8FF16B60" authorityName="Warncke" authorityYear="1967" box="[1305,1427,1791,1817]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Andrena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="455" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amicula">
<emphasis id="5FF7EAB8FF8DFF9DFAF7F91E8FF16B60" box="[1305,1427,1791,1817]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="455">A. amicula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) is distinctive, as similar 
<taxonomicName id="AA834D29FF8DFF9DFE4AF8C288446B44" box="[420,550,1827,1853]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Andrena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="456" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Aciandrena">
<emphasis id="5FF7EAB8FF8DFF9DFE4AF8C288446B44" box="[420,550,1827,1853]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="455">Aciandrena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species with similar short semi-squamous hairs have clear shagreenation on the scutal disc (e.g. 
<taxonomicName id="AA834D29FF8DFF9DFEA2F8A6880E6B18" authority="Warncke, 1968" authorityName="Warncke" authorityYear="1968" box="[332,620,1863,1889]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Andrena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="455" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hillana">
<emphasis id="5FF7EAB8FF8DFF9DFEA2F8A68BDB6B18" box="[332,441,1863,1889]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="455">A. hillana</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="09124B5BFF8DFF9DFE2EF8A6880E6B18" author="Warncke, K." box="[448,620,1863,1889]" pageId="4" pageNumber="455" pagination="1 - 110" refId="ref24222" refString="Warncke, K. (1968) Die Untergattungen der westpalaarktischen Bienengattung Andrena F. Memorias e Estudos do Museu Zoologico da Universidade de Coimbra, 307, 1 - 110." type="journal article" year="1968">Warncke, 1968</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="AA834D29FF8DFF9DFD98F8A689C06B18" authority="Warncke, 1974" authorityName="Warncke" authorityYear="1974" box="[630,930,1863,1889]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Andrena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="455" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pavonia">
<emphasis id="5FF7EAB8FF8DFF9DFD98F8A6888D6B18" box="[630,751,1863,1889]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="455">A. pavonia</emphasis>
Warncke, 1974
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="AA834D29FF8DFF9DFC32F8A68F746B18" authority="Warncke, 1974" authorityName="Warncke" authorityYear="1974" box="[988,1302,1863,1889]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Andrena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="455" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pellucida">
<emphasis id="5FF7EAB8FF8DFF9DFC32F8A68E016B18" box="[988,1123,1863,1889]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="455">A. pellucida</emphasis>
Warncke, 1974
</taxonomicName>
), and where such shagreenation is weak (e.g. 
<taxonomicName id="AA834D29FF8DFF9DFDE4F88A88F06BFC" authorityName="Warncke" authorityYear="1974" box="[522,658,1899,1925]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Andrena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="455" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pellucida">
<emphasis id="5FF7EAB8FF8DFF9DFDE4F88A88F06BFC" box="[522,658,1899,1925]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="455">A. pellucida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) it can be further separated by the broader foveae that are wider than the width of a flagellum (as wide as a flagellum in 
<taxonomicName id="AA834D29FF8DFF9DFD36F86E89026BD0" authorityName="Warncke" authorityYear="1974" box="[728,864,1935,1961]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Andrena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="455" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pellucida">
<emphasis id="5FF7EAB8FF8DFF9DFD36F86E89026BD0" box="[728,864,1935,1961]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="455">A. pellucida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). It can be separated from 
<taxonomicName id="AA834D29FF8DFF9DFB7EF86E8F406BD0" authority="Wood, 2021" authorityName="Wood" authorityYear="2021" box="[1168,1314,1935,1961]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Andrena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="455" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="palmyriae" status="spec. nov.">
<emphasis id="5FF7EAB8FF8DFF9DFB7EF86E8F406BD0" box="[1168,1314,1935,1961]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="455">A. palmyriae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="5FF7EAB8FF8DFF9DFAC7F86E8FFE6BD0" bold="true" box="[1321,1436,1935,1961]" pageId="4" pageNumber="455">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="44C457C3FF8DFF9DFAC7F86E8FFE6BD0" box="[1321,1436,1935,1961]" pageId="4" pageNumber="455" rank="species">spec. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(see below) because the process of the labrum is entire (not apically notched), the hind tibiae are dark (not orange), the nervulus is antefurcal (interstitial), and the tergal hair bands are shorter and less dense. In the male sex, complete diagnosis is difficult because many of the desert-living 
<taxonomicName id="AA834D29FF8CFF9CFCE9FF7689EB6CC8" box="[775,905,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Andrena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="456" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Aciandrena">
<emphasis id="5FF7EAB8FF8CFF9CFCE9FF7689EB6CC8" box="[775,905,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">Aciandrena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have been described only from the female sex, but the combination of yellow clypeus, granulose propodeal triangle, shiny scutum and scutellum, antefurcal nervulus, orange hind basitarsi, and genitalia with weakly produced gonocoxal teeth should be sufficient to facilitate identification, as most 
<taxonomicName id="AA834D29FF8CFF9CFE7AFEE288746D64" box="[404,534,259,285]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Andrena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="456" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Aciandrena">
<emphasis id="5FF7EAB8FF8CFF9CFE7AFEE288746D64" box="[404,534,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">Aciandrena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
males have more strongly produced gonocoxal teeth such as 
<taxonomicName id="AA834D29FF8CFF9CFB52FEE28AAD6D38" authority="Warncke, 1968" authorityName="Warncke" authorityYear="1968" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Andrena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="456" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spolata">
<emphasis id="5FF7EAB8FF8CFF9CFB52FEE28F4E6D64" box="[1212,1324,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">A. spolata</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="09124B5BFF8CFF9CFADCFEE28AAD6D38" author="Warncke, K." pageId="5" pageNumber="456" pagination="1 - 110" refId="ref24222" refString="Warncke, K. (1968) Die Untergattungen der westpalaarktischen Bienengattung Andrena F. Memorias e Estudos do Museu Zoologico da Universidade de Coimbra, 307, 1 - 110." type="journal article" year="1968">Warncke, 1968</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="F5B82A2FFF8CFF9CFF30FEC68B2C6D38" box="[222,334,295,321]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–12" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1648,1672]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1625]" captionTargetId="figure-20@4.[151,1436,181,1625]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 7–12. Andrena badiyah spec. nov. 7. male profile, 8. male face, 9. male scutum, 10. male terga, 11. male genitalia. Andrena spolata Warncke, 1968; 12. male genitalia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4556552" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4556552/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">Figure 12</figureCitation>
, see also photographs and notes in 
<bibRefCitation id="09124B5BFF8CFF9CFD37FEC689CC6D3B" author="Pisanty, G. &amp; Scheuchl, E. &amp; Dorchin, N." box="[729,942,295,322]" pageId="5" pageNumber="456" pagination="485 - 515" refId="ref23712" refString="Pisanty, G., Scheuchl, E. &amp; Dorchin, N. (2016) Eight new species of Andrena Fabricius (Hymenoptera: Apoidea: Andrenidae) from Israel - a Mediterranean hotspot for wild bees. Zootaxa, 4189 (3), 485 - 515. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4189.3.3" type="journal article" year="2016">
Pisanty 
<emphasis id="5FF7EAB8FF8CFF9CFCDCFEC689016D38" box="[818,867,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">et al</emphasis>
. 2016
</bibRefCitation>
). The genitalia are extremely close to 
<taxonomicName id="AA834D29FF8CFF9CFAB6FEC68AB76D1D" authorityName="Warncke" authorityYear="1974" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Andrena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="456" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pavonia">
<emphasis id="5FF7EAB8FF8CFF9CFAB6FEC68AB76D1D" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">A. pavonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but this species has a black clypeus (see 
<bibRefCitation id="09124B5BFF8CFF9CFD44FEAA8E716D1C" author="Gusenleitner, F. &amp; Schwarz, M." box="[682,1043,331,357]" pageId="5" pageNumber="456" pagination="1 - 1280" refId="ref23399" refString="Gusenleitner, F. &amp; Schwarz, M. (2002) Weltweite Checkliste der Bienengattung Andrena mit Bemerkungen und Erganzungen zu palaarktischen Arten (Hymenoptera, Apidae, Andreninae, Andrena). Entomofauna, Supplement 10, 1 - 1280." type="journal article" year="2002">Gusenleitner and Schwarz 2002</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="25996521FF8CFF9CFF29FE8E899B6DD4" pageId="5" pageNumber="456" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="6D3C36AAFF8CFF9CFF29FE8E899B6DD4" blockId="5.[151,1437,151,430]" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">
<emphasis id="5FF7EAB8FF8CFF9CFF29FE8E8B306DF0" bold="true" box="[199,338,367,393]" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">Etymology:</emphasis>
The name is derived from the Arabic name for the Syrian desert, the Badia (Arabic: Bâdiyah Ash-Shâm) that stretches over large parts of 
<collectingCountry id="1594763AFF8CFF9CFDBAFE7288F06DD4" box="[596,658,403,429]" name="Syria" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">Syria</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="1594763AFF8CFF9CFD73FE7288896DD4" box="[669,747,403,429]" name="Jordan" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">Jordan</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="1594763AFF8CFF9CFD18FE7289E86DD4" box="[758,906,403,429]" name="Saudi Arabia" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">Saudi Arabia</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry id="1594763AFF8CFF9CFC2BFE7289946DD4" box="[965,1014,403,429]" name="Iraq" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">Iraq</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
